    content: `<h2>Beating Visor Fog on British Roads</h2>
<p>Visor fogging is every UK rider's nemesis. Our damp climate creates perfect condensation conditions that can obscure vision at the worst possible moments. Whether crawling through Cotswolds morning mist or riding through rain on the A82, a fog-free visor is essential for safe touring.</p>
<h3>Why Visors Fog</h3>
<p>Fogging occurs when warm breath hits the cooler inner visor surface. Moisture condenses into tiny droplets that scatter light and reduce visibility. It worsens in cold weather, at low speeds where airflow cannot clear moisture, and when the visor is sealed against rain — exactly the conditions UK riders face most often.</p>
<h3>Pinlock Inserts: The Gold Standard</h3>
<p>A Pinlock insert is a secondary lens inside your visor held by two pins at either edge. The air gap acts as a thermal barrier preventing the inner surface from reaching dew point temperature. The insert has a moisture-absorbing coating that captures residual condensation before it can obscure vision.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pinlock 30</strong> — Basic anti-fog for dry mild conditions. Not recommended for UK touring.</li>
<li><strong>Pinlock 70</strong> — Enhanced protection suitable for most UK riding situations.</li>
<li><strong>Pinlock 120</strong> — Maximum protection with four times the absorption capacity. Essential for all-weather touring in British conditions.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Fitting a Pinlock Insert</h3>
<p>Most modern touring helmets are Pinlock-ready with two pins on the visor. Flex the insert slightly, hook one pin, then push onto the second. It should sit flat with an even air gap around the perimeter. If it bows outward or touches the visor, adjust pin positions by rotating the pins.</p>
<h3>Alternative Anti-Fog Solutions</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Anti-fog sprays</strong> — Apply a hydrophilic coating that prevents droplets forming. Effective but requires reapplication every few rides.</li>
<li><strong>Anti-fog wipes</strong> — Convenient single-use wipes. Keep several in your tank bag for mid-tour reapplication at fuel stops.</li>
<li><strong>Breath deflectors</strong> — Nose guards redirect exhaled air downward away from the visor. Effective combined with other treatments.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>A fogged visor is a genuine safety hazard, not just an inconvenience. Invest in a Pinlock 120 insert and replace it annually. Your vision and your safety are worth every penny.</blockquote>
<h3>Visor Care Tips</h3>
<p>Never clean Pinlock inserts with alcohol-based cleaners which strip the moisture-absorbing coating. Use only warm water and a soft cloth. Store in the protective pouch when not in use. Replace if scratched, yellowed, or no longer absorbing effectively. With proper care a Pinlock 120 lasts a full touring season of regular use.</p>`
