    content: `<h2>Building Your Complete Touring Luggage System</h2>
<p>A well-planned luggage system transforms your motorcycle from a day-ride machine into a capable touring platform. The key is choosing components that work together, balance the bike properly, and give you enough capacity without overloading. Getting this right is the difference between an enjoyable tour and a constant battle with handling and organisation.</p>
<h3>The Three-Point System</h3>
<p>Most touring setups use a three-point luggage system consisting of panniers for the bulk of your gear, a tank bag for essentials, and a top box or tail pack for overflow items. This distributes weight evenly and keeps the centre of gravity manageable.</p>
<h3>Capacity Planning</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weekend tour (2-3 days)</strong> — 40-60 litres total. A pair of small panniers or a single tail pack is sufficient.</li>
<li><strong>Week-long tour</strong> — 80-120 litres total. Full panniers plus tank bag. Add a tail pack if camping.</li>
<li><strong>Extended tour (2+ weeks)</strong> — 120-170 litres total. Full panniers, top box, tank bag. The maximum most bikes can safely carry.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Weight Distribution</h3>
<p>Proper weight distribution is critical for safe handling. Follow these principles:</p>
<p><strong>Keep weight low</strong> — Heavy items like tools, chain lube, and spare fluids go in the bottom of panniers. Light items like clothes go on top. Never strap heavy items on top of the seat stack.</p>
<p><strong>Balance side-to-side</strong> — Aim for equal weight in each pannier. An uneven load pulls the bike to one side, especially noticeable during slow-speed manoeuvres.</p>
<p><strong>Respect payload limits</strong> — Every motorcycle has a maximum payload (rider, passenger, and luggage combined). Check your owner's manual and do not exceed it.</p>
<h3>Recommended Systems</h3>
<p><strong>Budget system:</strong> Oxford Aqua panniers, Oxford magnetic tank bag, and an Oxford roll bag. Complete touring setup for under two hundred pounds.</p>
<p><strong>Mid-range system:</strong> GIVI Trekker Outback hard cases, SW-Motech tank ring bag, and Kriega US-20 tail pack. Secure, practical, and well-built for around eight hundred pounds.</p>
<p><strong>Premium system:</strong> SW-Motech TraX ADV aluminium cases, Kriega tank converter with US-20, and Kriega OS-18 top pack. The ultimate setup for serious touring at around fourteen hundred pounds.</p>
<blockquote>Pack light. It is the oldest touring advice and the best. Every kilogram you do not carry is a kilogram that does not affect your handling, fuel economy, or braking distance. If in doubt, leave it at home.</blockquote>
<h3>Security at Overnight Stops</h3>
<p>Hard cases with locks provide reasonable security for hotel stops but are not theft-proof. Never leave valuables visible in soft luggage. Consider a disc lock alarm for the bike itself and remove tank bags and valuables when leaving the bike unattended for extended periods.</p>`
