    affiliateLinks: [],
    content: `<h2>Why Knee Protection Matters</h2>
<p>Your knees are among the most exposed joints on a motorcycle. In a slide, the natural tendency is to spread your legs, putting your knees in direct contact with the road surface. The knee joint is complex, fragile, and extremely difficult to repair once damaged. Quality knee armour is not optional for touring — it is essential protection against life-altering injuries.</p>
<h3>CE Rating Standards</h3>
<p>Knee armour is tested to EN 1621-1 standard:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>CE Level 1</strong> — Average transmitted force below 35kN. Basic protection suitable for low-speed riding.</li>
<li><strong>CE Level 2</strong> — Average transmitted force below 20kN. Significantly better protection and the minimum recommended for touring riders on faster roads.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Armour Materials</h3>
<p><strong>Viscoelastic (D3O, SAS-TEC)</strong> — Flexible during normal movement but locks rigid on impact. The most comfortable option for long-distance touring as they flex naturally with your knee bend.</p>
<p><strong>Hard shell with foam</strong> — Traditional approach using a rigid outer shell over an energy-absorbing foam inner. Proven protection but less flexible and can create pressure points on long rides.</p>
<p><strong>Memory foam</strong> — Moulds to your knee shape over time for a custom fit. Good comfort but generally lower protection levels than viscoelastic alternatives.</p>
<h3>Positioning Is Everything</h3>
<p>The best knee armour in the world is useless if it is not centred over your kneecap. When buying riding trousers or jeans, check the armour sits correctly in both standing and sitting positions. Many trousers offer height-adjustable armour pockets to accommodate different leg proportions. If the armour migrates above or below your knee when riding, it cannot protect the joint effectively.</p>
<h3>Best Knee Armour 2026</h3>
<p><strong>D3O T5 EVO Pro</strong> — The premium CE Level 2 knee protector. Ultra-thin viscoelastic material that flexes freely but absorbs impacts efficiently. Comfortable for all-day touring without pressure points.</p>
<p><strong>SAS-TEC SC-1/06</strong> — Excellent CE Level 2 protector with viscoelastic construction. Slightly thicker than D3O but offers outstanding impact absorption at a lower price.</p>
<p><strong>Forcefield Isolator</strong> — Multi-layer CE Level 2 protector with ventilation channels. Flexible and breathable for warm-weather comfort.</p>
<p><strong>Oxford Level 2 Insert</strong> — Budget CE Level 2 protector that fits most standard trouser pockets. A worthwhile upgrade from any Level 1 armour.</p>
<blockquote>Always upgrade to CE Level 2 knee armour. The price difference between Level 1 and Level 2 is typically under twenty pounds. The protection difference could save your ability to walk.</blockquote>
<h3>Upgrading Factory Armour</h3>
<p>Many motorcycle trousers come with basic CE Level 1 knee armour. Upgrading to CE Level 2 is straightforward — simply remove the factory armour from its pocket and insert the upgrade. Most pockets accept standard-sized protectors from D3O, SAS-TEC, or Forcefield. This simple upgrade takes five minutes and significantly improves your knee protection for touring speeds.</p>`
