    affiliateLinks: [],
    content: `<h2>When Punctures Happen on Tour</h2>
<p>A puncture on a remote Highland road with no mobile signal and no passing traffic is every tourer's nightmare. While tubeless tyres on modern touring bikes are less prone to catastrophic failure than tubed tyres, punctures still happen. Carrying a compact repair kit and knowing how to use it means the difference between a 20-minute roadside fix and a very expensive recovery callout.</p>
<h3>Types of Repair</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Plug kit (mushroom plugs)</strong> — The most common roadside repair. A reaming tool cleans the puncture hole, then a mushroom-shaped rubber plug is inserted from inside the tyre using an insertion tool. Quick, effective for nail-type punctures, and allows you to ride to a tyre fitter for a proper repair.</li>
<li><strong>Rope plugs (string plugs)</strong> — Strips of sticky rubber inserted into the puncture using a needle tool. Quicker than mushroom plugs but generally considered less reliable for touring speeds. A temporary fix to get you to a garage.</li>
<li><strong>Tyre sealant</strong> — Liquid sealant injected through the valve. Works for small punctures but can unbalance the tyre and makes proper repair more difficult. Best kept as an emergency backup.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Essential Kit Contents</h3>
<p>A complete touring puncture repair kit should include:</p>
<p><strong>Reaming tool</strong> for cleaning the puncture hole. <strong>Plug insertion tool</strong> for fitting mushroom or string plugs. <strong>Selection of plugs</strong> in various sizes. <strong>CO2 inflator</strong> with at least three cartridges (one cartridge typically adds about 20psi to a motorcycle tyre). <strong>Small tyre pressure gauge</strong> for checking inflation. <strong>Valve core removal tool</strong> for adding sealant if needed. <strong>Latex gloves</strong> to keep your hands clean.</p>
<h3>Best Puncture Repair Kits</h3>
<p><strong>Stop and Go Pocket Tyre Plugger</strong> — Compact kit with mushroom plugs, CO2 inflator, and reaming tools. Fits easily in a pannier or tank bag. The mushroom plugs are among the most reliable available.</p>
<p><strong>Dynaplug Racer Pro</strong> — Ultra-compact plug insertion tool that combines reaming and insertion in one step. Brass-tipped plugs insert cleanly and hold securely. Premium-priced but excellent quality.</p>
<p><strong>Oxford CO2yre Repair Kit</strong> — Budget-friendly kit with string plugs and CO2 cartridges. Compact and effective for a temporary roadside repair.</p>
<blockquote>Practice using your repair kit at home before you need it roadside. The first time you use a plug kit should not be in the rain on a remote Scottish B-road with fading daylight. Familiarity with the process makes roadside repairs quicker and less stressful.</blockquote>
<h3>After a Repair</h3>
<p>A plug repair is a temporary fix. Ride cautiously to the nearest tyre fitter for a permanent internal repair or tyre replacement. Reduce your speed and avoid hard braking and acceleration. Check the plug every time you stop to ensure it is holding and the tyre pressure is stable.</p>`
