    content: `<h2>Cooking on Two Wheels</h2>
<p>A hot meal and a fresh brew at camp after a long day's riding is one of motorcycle touring's greatest pleasures. You do not need elaborate cooking equipment — a compact stove, a pot, and a few basics let you prepare everything from morning coffee to evening pasta. The key is keeping the kit lightweight, compact, and reliable.</p>
<h3>Stove Options</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Canister stoves</strong> — Screw-on stoves using threaded gas canisters. Light, reliable, and easy to use. The flame is adjustable for simmering. Canisters are widely available at outdoor shops and larger petrol stations across the UK.</li>
<li><strong>Integrated systems (JetBoil, MSR Windburner)</strong> — Stove and pot designed as one unit for maximum efficiency. They boil water incredibly fast and are very fuel-efficient. Slightly heavier and more expensive but excellent for riders who primarily want hot drinks and rehydrated meals.</li>
<li><strong>Alcohol stoves</strong> — Ultra-lightweight with no moving parts. Fuel is cheap and available everywhere. Slower to boil and harder to control flame, but weighs almost nothing.</li>
<li><strong>Solid fuel tablets</strong> — The lightest and simplest option. Fold-flat stove weighing under 50g. Very slow to boil but virtually indestructible and useful as an emergency backup.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Essential Cookware</h3>
<p><strong>Pot</strong> — A 750ml-1L titanium or aluminium pot with a lid handles all solo cooking needs. Titanium is lighter but aluminium distributes heat more evenly for cooking food rather than just boiling water.</p>
<p><strong>Mug</strong> — A double-wall titanium mug keeps drinks hot without burning your hands. Many nest inside the pot for compact packing.</p>
<p><strong>Spork</strong> — A combination spoon-fork handles all eating duties. Titanium or Lexan plastic versions weigh virtually nothing.</p>
<p><strong>Lighter and matches</strong> — Always carry both. A windproof lighter is your primary ignition and waterproof matches are the backup.</p>
<h3>Meal Ideas for Moto Camping</h3>
<p><strong>Breakfast:</strong> Porridge with dried fruit, coffee or tea. Instant porridge sachets are light, filling, and cook in two minutes. Pack ground coffee for a proper morning brew.</p>
<p><strong>Lunch:</strong> Eat at a cafe or pub — part of the touring experience. If cooking, couscous with tuna is quick, nutritious, and requires only boiling water.</p>
<p><strong>Dinner:</strong> Dehydrated camping meals have improved enormously. Brands like Firepot and Expedition Foods offer genuinely tasty freeze-dried meals that rehydrate in minutes. Alternatively, pasta with pesto and cheese is cheap, filling, and simple to cook.</p>
<blockquote>Never cook inside your tent. Carbon monoxide from gas stoves is deadly in enclosed spaces, and a knocked-over stove can ignite your tent fabric in seconds. Always cook in the vestibule with the door open or outside under a tarp.</blockquote>`
