    relatedSlugs: ["luggage-mounting-guide", "motorcycle-pre-tour-checklist", "motorcycle-luggage-systems"],
    affiliateLinks: [],
    content: `<h2>Why Suspension Setup Matters for Touring</h2>
<p>Loading your motorcycle with 30-50kg of luggage fundamentally changes how the suspension works. Without adjustment, the rear sags excessively, the front goes light, steering becomes vague, and the bike wallows through corners. Proper suspension setup for touring takes 15 minutes and transforms the loaded handling from dangerous to composed.</p>
<h3>Understanding Sag</h3>
<p>Sag is how much the suspension compresses under the weight of rider and luggage. Correct sag ensures the suspension has room to compress over bumps and extend into dips. Too much sag means the suspension bottoms out on bumps. Too little means it cannot absorb impacts properly.</p>
<p>For touring, aim for 30-35 percent sag at the rear — meaning the shock compresses by roughly a third of its total travel under your weight plus luggage. Most manufacturers specify this in the owner's manual.</p>
<h3>Adjusting Rear Preload</h3>
<p>Preload is the most important touring adjustment. Increasing rear preload compresses the spring to support the additional luggage weight and restore correct sag:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Remote preload adjuster</strong> — Many touring bikes have a knob or hydraulic adjuster that changes preload without tools. Turn it up when loaded, down when unloaded.</li>
<li><strong>Stepped adjusters</strong> — Some bikes use a stepped collar on the shock. Each step increases preload. Move up 2-3 steps when fully loaded.</li>
<li><strong>Electronic suspension</strong> — Premium bikes with semi-active suspension have a luggage mode that automatically adjusts preload and damping. Select this mode whenever carrying touring luggage.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Front Fork Adjustment</h3>
<p>Adding weight to the rear lightens the front, reducing steering feel and braking stability. If your forks have adjustable preload, increase it by 2-3 clicks when touring. If they have adjustable compression damping, increase it by 1-2 clicks to prevent dive under braking with the added rear weight.</p>
<h3>Damping Fine-Tuning</h3>
<p>Once preload is set, fine-tune the damping:</p>
<p><strong>Rebound damping</strong> — Controls how quickly the suspension extends after compression. Too fast and the bike bounces. Too slow and it packs down on successive bumps. Increase rebound damping by 1-2 clicks from your unloaded setting.</p>
<p><strong>Compression damping</strong> — Controls how quickly the suspension compresses over bumps. Increase slightly for touring to prevent bottoming on potholes and speed bumps with the added weight.</p>
<blockquote>Always check tyre pressures when loaded for touring. Most manufacturers recommend increasing rear tyre pressure by 0.2-0.3 bar when carrying luggage. Check your owner's manual for the specific loaded tyre pressure recommendation.</blockquote>
<h3>Recording Your Settings</h3>
<p>Keep a note of your suspension settings for different loading conditions. Write them in your owner manual or take a photo of the adjuster positions. This means you can quickly return to the correct setting when switching between touring and everyday riding rather than guessing each time.</p>`
