    relatedSlugs: ["motorcycle-panniers-guide", "touring-suspension-setup", "motorcycle-luggage-systems"],
    affiliateLinks: [],
    content: `<h2>Getting Your Luggage Right</h2>
<p>Properly mounting luggage on your motorcycle is critical for safety and handling. A loose pannier at speed is terrifying, and poorly positioned weight ruins the bike's handling characteristics. This guide walks you through the process of fitting panniers and top boxes correctly for safe, confident touring.</p>
<h3>Choosing the Right System</h3>
<p>Before buying luggage, identify what mounting systems are compatible with your specific motorcycle model. Most manufacturers offer model-specific frames and racks. Universal systems exist but require careful fitting to ensure they do not interfere with exhaust, suspension, or bodywork.</p>
<h3>Fitting Pannier Frames</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Remove the seat and any bodywork panels</strong> that overlap with the mounting points. This gives access to the subframe bolts.</li>
<li><strong>Offer up the frame</strong> to check alignment before tightening. The frame should sit parallel to the bike with even gaps on both sides.</li>
<li><strong>Use threadlock</strong> on all bolts. Vibration will loosen unthreadlocked fasteners over time, potentially causing the entire frame to shift.</li>
<li><strong>Check clearances</strong> with suspension at full compression. The panniers must not contact the swingarm, exhaust, or rear tyre under any circumstances.</li>
<li><strong>Test ride empty</strong> before loading. Check for rattles, vibrations, or interference with controls.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Top Box Installation</h3>
<p>Top boxes mount on a dedicated rear rack bolted to the subframe or pillion grab rail mounting points. Ensure the rack is rated for the weight you intend to carry — most racks have a maximum load of 5-10kg, which is easily exceeded with a full top box. Overloading a rack can cause structural failure at speed.</p>
<h3>Weight Distribution Rules</h3>
<p><strong>Keep weight low and centred:</strong> Heavy items in the bottom of panniers. Light items on top and in the top box. Equal weight left and right.</p>
<p><strong>Respect payload limits:</strong> Your bike has a maximum payload specified in the manual. This includes rider, passenger, and all luggage combined. Exceeding it compromises suspension, braking, and structural integrity.</p>
<p><strong>Secure everything:</strong> Nothing inside luggage should be able to shift under braking or cornering. Use packing cubes, roll straps, or dry bags to fill voids and prevent contents moving.</p>
<blockquote>After fitting new luggage, ride progressively for the first 50 miles. Start with gentle riding to check everything is secure and stable before building up to normal touring speeds. Stop after the first 20 miles to re-check all bolts and straps.</blockquote>
<h3>Quick-Release Systems</h3>
<p>Most modern pannier systems feature quick-release mechanisms for easy removal at hotels. Practice removing and refitting your panniers at home so you can do it quickly and confidently on tour. A fumbled pannier in a hotel car park scratches both the bike and your dignity.</p>`
