    affiliateLinks: [],
    content: `<h2>Getting Tyre Pressure Right on Tour</h2>
<p>Tyre pressure is the most overlooked safety factor in motorcycle touring. Incorrect pressure affects grip, handling, braking distance, fuel economy, and tyre life. A fully loaded touring motorcycle requires higher pressures than an unloaded bike, and many riders forget to adjust when they load up for a tour.</p>
<h3>Why Pressure Matters</h3>
<p>Under-inflated tyres flex excessively, generating heat that can cause a blowout at speed. They also wear unevenly on the shoulders and reduce fuel economy. Over-inflated tyres reduce the contact patch, compromising grip — especially dangerous in the wet conditions common on British roads. The sweet spot gives maximum grip while preventing overheating.</p>
<h3>Finding the Right Pressure</h3>
<p>Your motorcycle owner's manual provides pressure recommendations for different loading conditions. Typically you will find three settings:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Solo rider, no luggage</strong> — The lowest recommended pressure, usually 2.2-2.5 bar front and 2.5-2.9 bar rear.</li>
<li><strong>Solo rider with luggage</strong> — Slightly higher, typically adding 0.2 bar to the rear tyre to support the extra weight.</li>
<li><strong>Rider plus pillion with luggage</strong> — The highest setting, often 0.3-0.5 bar above solo pressure, especially at the rear.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Checking Pressure Correctly</h3>
<p>Always check tyre pressure when the tyres are cold — before riding or at least two hours after your last ride. Warm tyres show higher pressure due to heat expansion, giving a misleadingly high reading. Check every morning before the day's riding.</p>
<p>Invest in a quality digital pressure gauge. Petrol station gauges are notoriously inaccurate. A dedicated motorcycle gauge costs under twenty pounds and fits easily in your tank bag.</p>
<h3>Pressure Monitoring on Tour</h3>
<p>Tyre pressure monitoring systems (TPMS) provide real-time pressure readings on your dashboard or phone. Aftermarket TPMS kits from brands like Fobo and TireMoni use valve stem sensors that transmit to a handlebar display or smartphone app. They alert you immediately if pressure drops, potentially saving you from riding on a slowly deflating tyre.</p>
<blockquote>A 10 percent drop in tyre pressure reduces the tyre's load-carrying capacity by approximately 20 percent and increases rolling resistance significantly. On a loaded touring bike, this can mean the difference between a safe tyre and a dangerous one.</blockquote>
<h3>Temperature Effects</h3>
<p>British temperatures vary significantly between early morning and afternoon, and between seasons. A tyre inflated to 2.5 bar at 20 degrees will read approximately 2.3 bar at 5 degrees. During spring and autumn touring when temperature swings are large, check pressures more frequently to account for these natural variations.</p>`
