    content: `<h2>The 30-Point Pre-Tour Inspection</h2>
<p>A thorough pre-tour check takes about an hour and could save your entire trip. This comprehensive 30-point checklist covers every critical system on your motorcycle. Print it out, work through it methodically, and fix anything that fails before loading up for your adventure.</p>
<h3>Engine and Fluids</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>1. Engine oil level</strong> — Check on a level surface with the engine warm. Top up or change if due.</li>
<li><strong>2. Oil condition</strong> — Dark, gritty oil needs changing. Fresh golden oil means your engine is protected.</li>
<li><strong>3. Coolant level</strong> — Check in the overflow reservoir when cold. Top up with the correct specification coolant.</li>
<li><strong>4. Brake fluid front</strong> — Should be clear amber. Dark fluid needs replacing. Level should be between min and max marks.</li>
<li><strong>5. Brake fluid rear</strong> — Same checks as front. Rear brakes are often neglected but equally important.</li>
<li><strong>6. Clutch fluid</strong> — If hydraulic, check level and condition. Low fluid can cause clutch slip or drag.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Wheels and Tyres</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>7. Front tyre tread depth</strong> — Minimum 2mm recommended, 1mm legal minimum. Check across the full width.</li>
<li><strong>8. Rear tyre tread depth</strong> — Same standards. Rear tyres wear faster than fronts on most bikes.</li>
<li><strong>9. Tyre condition</strong> — Check for cracks, bulges, cuts, and embedded objects. Replace if any damage is found.</li>
<li><strong>10. Tyre pressure</strong> — Set to manufacturer's loaded touring specification when cold.</li>
<li><strong>11. Wheel bearings</strong> — Rock each wheel side to side. Any play means replacement needed.</li>
<li><strong>12. Wheel spokes</strong> — If wire wheels, check spoke tension. A loose spoke can cause wheel failure.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Brakes and Suspension</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>13. Front brake pad thickness</strong> — Check both sides. Replace if below 2mm remaining material.</li>
<li><strong>14. Rear brake pad thickness</strong> — Same standard. Rear pads often wear faster with luggage weight.</li>
<li><strong>15. Brake disc condition</strong> — Check for scoring, warping, and minimum thickness stamps.</li>
<li><strong>16. Fork seals</strong> — Check for oil weeping around the fork stanchions. Leaking seals reduce damping and contaminate brake pads.</li>
<li><strong>17. Rear shock</strong> — Check for leaks and adjust preload for loaded touring weight.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Drive System</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>18. Chain tension</strong> — Adjust to manufacturer specification. Usually 25-35mm of slack.</li>
<li><strong>19. Chain condition</strong> — Check for stiff links, excessive rust, and worn O-rings.</li>
<li><strong>20. Sprocket wear</strong> — Look for hooked or pointed teeth indicating replacement needed.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Electrical</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>21. Headlight</strong> — Check main and dip beam function and alignment.</li>
<li><strong>22. Indicators</strong> — All four must flash at the correct rate.</li>
<li><strong>23. Brake light</strong> — Activated by both front lever and rear pedal.</li>
<li><strong>24. Horn</strong> — Must be audible. A weak horn needs replacement.</li>
<li><strong>25. Battery</strong> — Clean terminals, tight connections, and holds charge overnight.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Controls and Final Checks</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>26. Throttle</strong> — Should snap shut when released. Check for fraying cables.</li>
<li><strong>27. Clutch</strong> — Smooth engagement with correct free play at the lever.</li>
<li><strong>28. Mirrors</strong> — Secure and adjustable. Replace if cracked or loose.</li>
<li><strong>29. Fasteners</strong> — Check critical bolts: axle nuts, brake calipers, engine mounts, subframe bolts.</li>
<li><strong>30. Documents</strong> — Valid MOT, insurance, driving licence, breakdown cover details packed and accessible.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>If any point on this checklist raises doubt, fix it before you leave. The cost of a repair at home is always less than the cost of a breakdown on tour, both financially and in ruined riding days.</blockquote>`
