    content: `<h2>Charging Your Electric Motorcycle Across the UK</h2>
<p>Understanding the UK's charging network is essential for electric motorcycle touring. While the network is expanding rapidly, it is not yet as ubiquitous or reliable as petrol stations. Knowing which networks to use, which apps to download, and how to plan your charging stops transforms electric touring from stressful to enjoyable.</p>
<h3>UK Charging Networks</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Tesla Supercharger</strong> — Now open to non-Tesla vehicles including motorcycles with CCS connectors. Fast and reliable but check the app for motorcycle accessibility as some locations have awkward cable lengths.</li>
<li><strong>Gridserve Electric Highway</strong> — Found at motorway service stations across the UK. Reliable DC fast charging with contactless payment. Generally motorcycle-accessible.</li>
<li><strong>BP Pulse</strong> — Widespread network with chargers at many BP forecourts and car parks. Mixed reliability but improving. The app is essential for locating available chargers.</li>
<li><strong>Pod Point</strong> — Common at supermarkets and retail parks. Mostly AC charging (slower) but useful for topping up while shopping or eating.</li>
<li><strong>Osprey Charging</strong> — Growing network of fast chargers at convenient locations. Generally well-maintained with contactless payment.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Essential Apps</h3>
<p><strong>Zap-Map</strong> — The definitive UK charging map showing all networks, charger types, real-time availability, and user reviews. Essential for planning routes and finding chargers. The community updates identify broken chargers quickly.</p>
<p><strong>A Better Route Planner (ABRP)</strong> — Route planning app that calculates charging stops based on your bike's range, speed, and battery capacity. It accounts for elevation, weather, and driving style to give realistic range estimates.</p>
<h3>Practical Charging Tips</h3>
<p><strong>Plan your stops:</strong> Unlike petrol touring where you refuel when the tank gets low, electric touring requires planning charging stops in advance. Map your route around charger locations and always have a backup charger identified in case your primary choice is occupied or broken.</p>
<p><strong>Charge to 80 percent:</strong> Charging from 80 to 100 percent takes almost as long as charging from 10 to 80 percent. For touring efficiency, charge to 80 and move on rather than waiting for a full battery.</p>
<p><strong>Carry adapters:</strong> A Type 2 to three-pin adapter lets you charge from a standard domestic socket in an emergency. It is painfully slow but could save you from being stranded at a remote B&B with no public charger nearby.</p>
<blockquote>Always arrive at a charger with at least 15-20 percent battery remaining. Charger reliability is not guaranteed, and arriving with a dead battery at a broken charger is a deeply stressful situation.</blockquote>
<h3>Charging Etiquette</h3>
<p>Do not hog chargers once your bike is charged. Move it promptly so the next user can plug in. If a charger has a queue, be patient and courteous. The electric vehicle community is generally friendly and helpful — many car drivers are curious about electric motorcycles and happy to share charger knowledge.</p>`
