    content: `<h2>Making the Back Seat Bearable</h2>
<p>Factory pillion seats are often an afterthought — thin, narrow, and uncomfortable after 30 minutes. If you want your passenger to enjoy touring rather than endure it, investing in pillion comfort upgrades is essential. The good news is that relatively modest investments can dramatically improve the rear riding experience.</p>
<h3>Seat Upgrades</h3>
<p>The seat is the most impactful upgrade. Options range from simple bolt-on solutions to fully custom seats:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Gel seat pads</strong> — Products like AirHawk Air Pad or Wild Ass cushion sit on top of the existing seat. Air cells distribute pressure and reduce numbness. The cheapest and easiest upgrade at around forty to sixty pounds.</li>
<li><strong>Custom pillion seats</strong> — Companies like Corbin and Sargent create seats with better foam density, wider bases, and improved shapes. Expensive but transformative for regular pillion touring.</li>
<li><strong>Sheepskin covers</strong> — A genuine sheepskin cover adds cushioning and breathability. They look slightly eccentric but the comfort improvement is genuine.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Backrests</h3>
<p>A backrest gives the pillion something to lean against under acceleration and prevents them sliding backward on the seat. Options include dedicated passenger backrests that bolt to the subframe, top boxes that double as backrests, and adjustable systems that fold away when not carrying a passenger. A top box with a comfortable pad is the most practical solution as it provides luggage space and a backrest simultaneously.</p>
<h3>Footpeg Upgrades</h3>
<p>Standard pillion footpegs are often small and poorly positioned. Wider aftermarket pegs reduce pressure points on the soles and allow the pillion to shift their feet for comfort. Lowering kits reposition the pegs downward, reducing knee angle for taller passengers. Rubber-mounted pegs reduce vibration transmitted through the feet.</p>
<h3>Wind Protection</h3>
<p>Pillions sit higher and more exposed than riders. If your bike has a tall screen that protects you but deflects turbulence onto your pillion, consider a different screen height or profile. Some manufacturers offer pillion-specific wind deflectors that attach to the rear of the bike.</p>
<h3>Heating and Electronics</h3>
<p><strong>Heated seat</strong> — Aftermarket heated seat pads plug into the bike's 12V system. A warm seat on a cold morning is deeply appreciated by pillions.</p>
<p><strong>Intercom</strong> — A Bluetooth intercom system in the pillion's helmet is essential. Communication prevents frustration and improves safety.</p>
<p><strong>Entertainment</strong> — Some intercom systems let the pillion listen to music or podcasts independently. On long motorway stretches, this dramatically reduces boredom.</p>
<blockquote>Ask your pillion what bothers them most about riding as a passenger. The answer might surprise you — it could be wind noise, seat pressure, cold feet, or simply boredom. Address their specific complaint and you both enjoy touring more.</blockquote>`
